h <i>hǣth</i> ‘heathland, heather’ + <i>lēah</i>.","In some cases also Native American (Navajo): variant of   Hatathlie   ‘singer (i.e. medicine man)’. Compare   Singer   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatathlie","meanings":["Native American (Navajo): from an American English altered (and shortened) form of a Navajo personal name such as <i>Hataałii Yázhí</i>, based on the occupational name <i>hataałii</i> which means literally ‘singer’ and denotes a medicine man. Compare   Hadley   2 and   Singer   6."]}]},{"name":"Alan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alan Hadley ,Lord of Hadley was born about 1130, in Hadley, Shropshire, England, his father, William Hadley, was 32 and his mother, Seburga or Sibil Peverell, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter with Alice Pantulf. He died in 1194, in his hometown, at the age of 65."},"et":{"ABT 1130  (eldest son)–1194":"umbes 1130–1194","1130–1194":"1130–1194","–1190":"–1190","–1194":"–1194","1174–1225":"1174–1225","1100–1136":"1100–1136","1105–1154":"1105–1154","1190":"1190","1105":"1105","1225":"1225","1136":"1136","1100":"1100","ABT 1130  (eldest son)":"umbes 1130","1154":"1154","1174":"1174","1130":"1130","after 1154":"pärast 1154","1194":"1194","Hadley, Shropshire, England":"Hadley, Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1130  (eldest son)–1194":"noin 1130–1194","1130–1194":"1130–